name: American chop suey
description: An American dish of elbow macaroni, ground beef, tomato sauce, seasonings, and sometimes grated cheese.

name: American goulash
description: A dish that is similar to American chop suey, consisting of pasta (such as macaroni or egg noodles), ground beef, tomatoes or tomato sauce, and seasonings. Some variations include cheese.

name: Barbecue spaghetti
description: Spaghetti noodles topped with a sauce made from smoked pork, vegetables, and barbecue sauce.

name: Biscuits and gravy
description: Soft dough biscuits, generally split into halves and covered in either sawmill or sausage gravy.

name: Borracho beans
description: Pinto beans cooked with beer, pork or bacon, and spices such as onions, garlic, and jalapeño peppers. A Tex-Mex dish; the name means "drunken beans".

name: Cheese straws
description: A savory biscuit-like snack made with flour, butter, salt, cheddar cheese, and cayenne pepper; sometimes the dough is extruded through a cookie press before being baked

name: Chili burger
description: Also known as a chili size. A hamburger (or cheeseburger) topped with chili con carne.

name: Chimichanga
description: A deep-fried burrito, usually made with a flour tortilla and various fillings such as beans, rice, cheese, and some type of meat.

name: Chislic
description: Small cubes of mutton (or sometimes beef, pork, or venison), deep-fried and served on skewers or toothpicks.

name: City chicken
description: Cubes of meat (usually pork) which have been placed on a wooden skewer (approximately 4–5 inches (10–13 cm) long), then fried or baked.

name: Eggs Sardou
description: Poached eggs, artichoke bottoms, creamed spinach, and hollandaise sauce, sometimes with other ingredients such as anchovies or chopped ham.

name: Étouffée
description: Étouffée (/eɪtuːˈfeɪ/ ay-too-FAY) is crawfish (or sometimes other shellfish such as shrimp or crabs) cooked using a technique called smothering, with roux, Cajun spices, and other ingredients, and served with rice.

name: Fried cheese curds
description: Cheese curds that are battered and deep fried.

name: Frito pie
description: A dish made with chili, cheese, and corn chips (especially Fritos). Additions can include pico de gallo, refried beans, sour cream, onions, rice, and jalapeños.

name: Garbage Plate
description: A choice of two entrees such as cheeseburger, hamburger, red hots, white hots, Italian sausage, chicken tenders, fried haddock, fried ham, grilled cheese, or eggs; and two sides of either home fries, French fries, baked beans, or macaroni salad; topped with mustard, onions, and a meat sauce of slowly simmered ground beef and spices; usually served with Italian bread and butter on the side.

name: Goetta
description: Goetta (/ˈɡɛtə/ GHET-ə) is ground pork or beef mixed with steel-cut oats and seasonings, formed into a log, sliced, and fried.  It originated in the Over-the-Rhine neighborhood of Cincinnati.

name: Grillades
description: Grillades (/ɡriːˈjɑːdz/ gree-YAHDZ) are fried or seared medallions of meat, usually beef, cooked with Creole-style vegetables and spices.

name: Hotdish
description: A variety of casserole which typically contains a starch, a meat or other protein, and a canned or frozen vegetable, mixed with canned soup

name: Hushpuppy
description: A savory food made from cornmeal batter that is deep fried or baked rolled as a small ball

name: Johnny Marzetti
description: A Midwestern Italian American pasta dish consisting of noodles, cheese, ground beef, and a tomato sauce that typically includes aromatic vegetables and mushrooms.

name: Klobásník
description: A klobasnek (meaning "sausage roll") is an American Czech savory finger food. Unlike kolaches, which are sweet and which came to the United States with Czech immigrants, klobasneks were first made by Czechs who settled in Texas.

name: Laulau
description: A traditional preparation consisting of pork wrapped in taro leaf

name: Livermush
description: A dish made with pig liver and other parts mixed with cornmeal, formed into a loaf, and fried.

name: Loco moco
description: There are many variations, but the traditional loco moco consists of white rice, topped with a hamburger patty, a fried egg, and brown gravy

name: Mission burrito
description: A very large burrito filled with meat, beans, rice, and additional flavor-enhancing ingredients such as cheese, sour cream, guacamole, pico de gallo, or jalapeños.  Typically served wrapped in aluminum foil.

name: Natchitoches meat pie
description: Ground beef, ground pork, onions, peppers, garlic, oil, and a pie shell

name: Pasty
description: A baked pastry, a traditional variety of which is filled with beef, pork, lamb, or venison, with onions, potatoes, and carrots. Usually handheld with a crispy outer crust.

name: Pudding corn
description: Also known as corn pudding.  A savory, baked casserole made with corn kernels (and sometimes cornmeal), eggs, cream or milk, and other ingredients.  Usually served as a side dish.

name: Runza
description: A hand-held meat pie similar to a bierock, with a yeast dough bread pocket and a filling of ground beef, shredded cabbage, and seasonings.

name: Scrapple
description: Traditionally, a mush of pork scraps and trimmings combined with cornmeal and wheat flour, often buckwheat flour, and spices

name: Slinger
description: A diner specialty typically consisting of two eggs, hash browns, and a beef patty, all covered in chili con carne and topped with cheese and onions.

name: Spam musubi
description: A piece of grilled Spam on top of a rice ball, held together with a strip of nori.  This is similar to nigiri sushi, but with Spam instead of raw fish.

name: Spoonbread
description: A moist cornmeal-based dish, similar in consistency and taste to Yorkshire pudding.  (Pictured is spoonbread underneath a pork chop, with a side of greens.)

name: Steamed cheeseburger
description: Ground beef is steamed on a tray to create a juicy patty without any grease. Steamed cheese, raw onion and mustard toppings are added afterwards.

name: Stromboli
description: A type of savory turnover filled with various cheeses, typically mozzarella, Italian meats such as salami, capicola and bresaola or vegetables, and traditionally wrapped in Italian bread dough. It was invented in 1950 at Romano's Pizzeria & Italian Restaurant in Essington, Pennsylvania, by Nazzareno "Nat" Romano.

name: Succotash
description: A chunky dish that consists primarily of sweet corn with lima beans or other shell beans. Other ingredients may be added including tomatoes and green or sweet red peppers.

name: Toasted ravioli
description: A dish of breaded, deep-fried ravioli, found on the menus of many St. Louis restaurants including those of the Hill, a predominantly Italian neighborhood.

name: Anadama bread
description: A traditional yeast bread of New England made with wheat flour, cornmeal, molasses and sometimes rye flour

name: Beaten biscuits
description: A dense biscuit, sometimes served with ham.  Before baking the dough is beaten extensively with a rolling pin or other blunt instrument.

name: Hot water corn bread
description: Cornbread made by mixing cornmeal and water and cooking the resulting batter in a skillet with cooking oil.

name: Johnnycakes
description: Also known as hoecakes. Cornmeal flatbread, a dish of Native American origin.

name: Parker House roll
description: A bread roll that was invented at the Parker House Hotel in Boston during the 1870s. It may be served as a side dish.

name: Buffalo wings
description: Chicken wing sections (wingettes and drumettes) that are deep-fried, unbreaded, and coated in a hot sauce made with cayenne pepper, vinegar, and butter. Usually served with celery or carrot sticks, and bleu cheese or ranch dressing for dipping.

name: Chicken and waffles
description: The soul food version of chicken and waffles, popular in the South, pairs fried chicken with a breakfast waffle.  The Pennsylvania Dutch version, found in the Northeast, consists of a plain waffle with pulled, stewed chicken on top, covered in gravy.

name: Chicken Divan
description: A chicken casserole usually served with broccoli, almonds, and Mornay sauce. It was named after the place of its invention, the Divan Parisienne Restaurant in the Chatham Hotel.

name: Chicken riggies
description: An Italian-American pasta dish of chicken, rigatoni, and hot or sweet peppers, in a spicy cream and tomato sauce.

name: Hot chicken
description: A portion of breast, thigh, or wing that has been marinated in buttermilk, floured, fried, and finally sauced using an oil-based paste that has been spiced with cayenne pepper.

name: Moravian chicken pie
description: A savory pie containing no vegetables and filled only with chicken meat and a small amount of thickened broth. Served with hot chicken gravy on top.

name: Bananas Foster
description: A dessert made from bananas and vanilla ice cream, with a sauce made from butter, brown sugar, cinnamon, dark rum, and banana liqueur. The butter, sugar and bananas are cooked, then the alcohol is added and ignited as a flambé. The bananas and sauce are served over the ice cream.

name: Beignet
description: A beignet (/bɛnˈjeɪ/ ben-YAY) is a square-shaped pastry made with deep-fried choux dough and topped with powdered sugar.

name: Chantilly cake
description: A modified German chocolate cake without coconut or nuts in its frosting, although it is occasionally topped with macadamia nuts.

name: Chess pie
description: A simple, sweet custard-like pie that is made from eggs, butter, sugar, and optionally a flavoring such as lemon, orange, or chocolate.

name: Derby pie
description: Derby pie is a chocolate and walnut tart in a pie shell with a pastry dough crust.

name: Doberge cake
description: Doberge (/doʊˈbɜːrʒ/ doh-BURZH) cake is a cake with many thin layers, separated with dessert pudding (often half chocolate and half lemon), and with a glazed outer frosting.

name: Fortune cookie
description: A crisp, sugary cookie wafer usually made from flour, sugar, vanilla and sesame seed oil, containing a piece of paper inside bearing a "fortune", usually an aphorism or a vague prophecy, and typically served after a Chinese meal. Makoto Hagiwara of the Tea House in the Japanese Tea Garden in San Francisco's Golden Gate Park reportedly first served the modern version of the cookie in the 1890s or early 1900s.

name: Frozen banana
description: Made by putting a banana on a stick, freezing it, and dipping it in melted chocolate. May be covered with toppings such as chopped nuts, sprinkles, sugar, and crushed cookies.

name: Gooey butter cake
description: A flat, dense cake made with yellow box cake mix, butter, sugar, and eggs, and cream cheese typically about 1 inch (2.5 cm) tall, and can be dusted with powdered sugar.

name: Happy Cake
description: A tropical cake prepared with pineapple, coconut and macadamia nuts, it is often referred to as Hawaii's version of a fruit cake.

name: Haupia
description: Haupia (/haʊˈpiːə/ how-PEE-ə) is a dish in the native cuisine of Hawaii, it is a coconut milk-based Hawaiian dessert often found at luaus and other local gatherings in Hawaiʻi

name: Hummingbird cake
description: A banana-pineapple spice cake that has been a tradition in Southern cuisine since the mid-20th century. The first known publication of the recipe, as written by L.H. Wiggin, was in the February 1978 issue of Southern Living.

name: Key lime pie
description: A pie made with key lime juice, egg yolks, and sweetened condensed milk, with a meringue topping.

name: King cake
description: A cake made of braided pastry laced with cinnamon, with purple, green, and gold frosting, and a small plastic baby hidden inside.  Eaten during Mardi Gras season.

name: Kulolo
description: A dessert made from mashed kalo (taro) corms, grated coconut meat or coconut milk, and sugar

name: Lane cake
description: Also known as a prize cake; a bourbon-soaked layer cake

name: Mud pie
description: A chocolate-based dessert pie.

name: Modjeska
description: A marshmallow dipped in caramel.

name: Moravian sugar cake
description: A traditional sweet coffee cake topped with butter, brown sugar and cinnamon which was popularized by Moravians in North Carolina.

name: Pecan pie
description: A pie made primarily of eggs and corn syrup with pecan nuts.

name: Salt water taffy
description: Originally produced and marketed in the Atlantic City, New Jersey area starting in the 1880s

name: Shaker lemon pie
description: A pie with a filling made with whole lemons that have been sliced extremely thin and macerated with sugar.

name: Shoofly pie
description: A pie with a cake-like consistency, made with molasses.

name: Snickers salad
description: A mix of Snickers bars, Granny Smith apples, whipped cream, and often pudding or whipped topping, served in a bowl.

name: Strawberry rhubarb pie
description: A sweet and tart pie made with strawberries and rhubarb, with a latticed top crust.

name: Sugar on snow
description: Also known as "tire sur la neige" (French for "pull over snow"). A candy made by boiling maple syrup and pouring it over clean snow to harden it. Popular at seasonal "sugaring-off" events where freshly tapped maple syrup is boiled and guests receive a small spoon or popscile stick to roll the still-warm maple onto.

name: Toll House cookie
description: A cookie made with butter, brown sugar, and white sugar, with semi-sweet chocolate chips.  Invented at the Toll House Inn in Whitman, Massachusetts.

name: Tipsy cake
description: A variation on the English trifle brought to America in colonial times. A cake made with an alcoholic beverage such as wine, sherry, or bourbon, and often with custard, jam, or fruit.

name: Whoopie pie
description: A baked product made of two round mound-shaped pieces of chocolate cake with a sweet, creamy filling or frosting sandwiched between them.

name: Cioppino
description: Cioppino (/tʃoʊˈpiːnoʊ/ choh-PEE-noh) is an Italian-American fish stew with tomatoes and a variety of fish and shellfish.

name: Clambake
description: Seafood and vegetables steamed between layers of seaweed over hot rocks on a beach.

name: Clam cakes
description: Fritter made from flour, water, baking powder, clam juice, and chopped or minced clams (usually quahogs) all mixed together, rolled into balls and deep fried.

name: Clams casino
description: A clam served on a half clamshell, topped with breadcrumbs and crumbled bacon, and broiled.

name: Fish boil
description: Freshwater whitefish, potatoes, and onions are boiled in a large pot of salty water, with the fish and potatoes in wire baskets.  When the fish is ready, the fish oil, which has floated to the top, is removed, traditionally with burning kerosene.

name: Frogmore stew
description: Frogmore stew, also known as low country boil, is a dish consisting of shell-on shrimp, smoked sausage, corn, and red potatoes all cooked together in a spice laden broth. It's typically served family style, on newspaper with lemon, cocktail sauce, and drawn butter.

name: Hangtown fry
description: Hangtown fry is a type of omelette made famous during the California Gold Rush in the 1850s. The most common version includes bacon and oysters combined with eggs, and fried together.

name: Lobster Newberg
description: An American seafood dish made from lobster, butter, cream, cognac, sherry, eggs, and cayenne pepper.

name: Oysters Bienville
description: A traditional dish in New Orleans cuisine,

name: Oysters Rockefeller
description: Oysters on the half-shell that have been topped with various other ingredients (often parsley and other green herbs, a rich butter sauce and bread crumbs) and are then baked or broiled

name: Shrimp and grits
description: Grits with cooked shrimp added, usually served for breakfast.

name: Shrimp DeJonghe
description: A casserole of large, peeled shrimp, soft breadcrumbs, and a rich sauce made with butter, garlic, and white wine or sherry.

name: Stuffies
description: Also known as stuffed clams or stuffed quahogs. Quahog clams, minced and mixed with breadcrumbs and sometimes other ingredients, baked on the half-shell.

name: Squid lū'au
description: Made with squid (or octopus), taro (lu'au) leaves, coconut milk, garlic, water, and Hawaiian salt. (Squid lū'au is pictured at the very bottom of the image.)

name: Bagel dog
description: A full-size or miniature hot dog, wrapped in bagel-style breading before or after cooking.

name: Beer brat
description: A bratwurst simmered in beer and then grilled.

name: Boudin
description: A sausage made with pork, rice, and Cajun spices.

name: Coney
description: A hot dog topped with a spiced meat sauce called Cincinnati chili, mustard, diced onions, and sometimes cheese.

name: Coney Island hot dog
description: A large, natural-casing hot dog topped with a hearty, mildly spiced meat sauce, and with mustard and diced onions.

name: Dodger Dog
description: A 10-inch (25 cm) hot dog wrapped in a steamed bun.

name: Maxwell Street Polish
description: A Polish sausage made with beef and pork, and with garlic and other spices.  Served on a bun with grilled onions.

name: Michigan hot dog
description: A natural-casing hot dog made of beef and pork, sometimes bright red in color, on a steamed bun, topped with a meat sauce made with hamburger meat, tomatoes, and spices.  Optionally also topped with onions and yellow mustard.

name: New York System wiener
description: A sausage similar to a hot dog, made of veal and pork, served in a steamed bun, and topped with celery salt, yellow mustard, chopped onions, and a seasoned meat sauce made from ground beef.

name: Polish Boy
description: A kielbasa sausage covered with French fries, barbecue sauce, and cole slaw, served in a long bun.

name: Ripper
description: A hot dog that is deep-fried until the casing rips.

name: Sonoran hot dog
description: A hot dog wrapped in bacon and grilled, served on a bolillo-style hot dog bun, and topped with pinto beans, onions, tomatoes, and a variety of additional condiments, often including mayonnaise, mustard, and jalapeño salsa.

name: White hot
description: A hot dog made with a combination of uncured and unsmoked pork, beef, and veal.  The lack of smoking or curing allows the meat to retain a naturally white color.  White hots usually contain mustard and other spices, and often include a dairy component such as nonfat dry milk.

name: Grandma pizza
description: Thin-crust pizza topped sparingly with shredded mozzarella, crushed uncooked canned tomatoes, chopped garlic, and olive oil, cooked in a rectangular pan and then cut into squares.

name: Pizza bagel
description: The two halves of a toasted bagel, baked with tomato sauce, mozzarella cheese, and often other pizza toppings.

name: Pizza puff
description: A deep-fried dough pocket filled with cheese, tomato sauce, and other pizza ingredients such as sausage.  Can be found at some hot dog stands and casual dining restaurants.

name: Tomato pie
description: Thick-crust pizza dish cooked with cheese underneath a large amount of garlicky tomato sauce, cooled to room temperature before serving.

name: Funeral potatoes
description: A casserole of hash browns or grated/cubed potatoes, Cheddar or Parmesan cheese, cream soup or a cream sauce, and other ingredients, topped with corn flakes or crushed potato chips.

name: Jo Jo potatoes
description: Potato wedges that are fried in the same vat as chicken,

name: Potatoes O'Brien
description: Pan-fried potatoes along with green and red bell peppers.

name: Salt potatoes
description: As the potatoes cook, the salty water forms a crust on the skin and seals the potatoes so they never taste waterlogged

name: Charleston red rice
description: Long grain rice cooked with crushed tomatoes, small bits of bacon or smoked pork sausage, celery, bell peppers, and onions.

name: Dirty rice
description: Rice cooked with small amounts of meat (traditionally chicken giblets) which give it a dark color, along with onions, bell peppers, celery, and spices.

name: Hoppin' John
description: Rice cooked with black-eyed peas or field peas, chopped onion, and sliced bacon.  Sometimes country sausage, ham hock, fatback, or another type of meat is used instead of bacon.

name: Jambalaya
description: A dish of rice and meat in Creole cuisine (often a combination of andouille sausage, chicken, and shrimp) cooked with vegetables and Creole spices.

name: Red beans and rice
description: A dish in Creole cuisine, it is prepared with kidney beans cooked with Cajun spices, and often also cooked with ham and vegetables such as bell peppers, onions, and celery, served together with white rice.

name: Rice and gravy
description: Traditionally a brown gravy based on pan drippings, cooked with onions, bell peppers, celery, and seasonings, and served over steamed or boiled rice.  Now often made with various types of meats.

name: Crab Louie
description: Iceberg lettuce with Dungeness crab or other crab meat, hard boiled eggs, tomatoes, and Louis dressing.

name: Frogeye salad
description: A pasta salad that is made with acini di pepe pasta, whipped topping and egg yolks. Fruit, such as mandarin oranges and pineapples, are often mixed in, and it is sometimes topped with marshmallows.

name: Poke
description: Poke (/ˈpoʊkeɪ/ POH-kay) is a raw seafood salad served as an appetizer in Hawaiian cuisine.  It is most commonly made with yellowfin tuna, salty seaweed, and sweet onions.

name: Seven-layer salad
description: A salad with seven layers, usually composed of iceberg lettuce, peas, tomatoes, onions, Cheddar cheese, bacon, and mayonnaise.  Served in a glass bowl with high sides.

name: Shrimp Louie
description: Iceberg lettuce with Pacific pink shrimp or other small boiled and shelled shrimp, hard boiled eggs, tomatoes, and Louis dressing; basically the same ingredients as a Crab Louie salad, but with shrimp instead of Dungeness crab

name: Waldorf salad
description: First created between 1893 and 1896 at the Waldorf Hotel, it is generally made of fresh apples, celery and walnuts, dressed in mayonnaise.

name: Beef Manhattan
description: An open-faced sandwich of roast beef and gravy, served with mashed potatoes.

name: Beef on weck
description: Thin-sliced roast beef on a Kümmelweck roll (a Kaiser roll topped with caraway seeds and salt).  The cut face of the top half of the roll may be dipped in the jus from the roast. Horseradish is usually provided for the diner to spread to taste on the top half of the roll.

name: Cheesesteak
description: Also known as a Philly cheesesteak.  Thinly sliced beef and melted cheese (generally Cheez Whiz, American cheese, or Provolone) on a hoagie roll, typically with sauteed onions and other seasonings.

name: Chopped cheese
description: Ground beef with onions, topped by melted cheese, and served with lettuce, tomatoes and condiments on a hero roll.

name: Cuban sandwich
description: A pressed sandwich made with sliced ham and roasted pork, Swiss cheese, pickles, mustard, and sometimes Genoa salami, on Cuban bread. Medianoche sandwiches are very closely related.

name: Fluffernutter
description: Made with peanut butter and marshmallow fluff, usually served on white bread

name: Fool's Gold Loaf
description: A French bread, baked and hollowed out, and filled with a jar of peanut butter, a jar of grape jelly, and a pound of bacon.

name: French dip
description: Thin-sliced beef served on a French roll, often topped with Swiss cheese and onions. Traditionally, the bread is dipped in the beef juice that results from cooking, though it's not unusual for the jus to be served on the side.

name: Fried-brain sandwich
description: A sandwich made with heavily battered sliced calves' brains, deep fried and served on sliced bread.

name: Gerber sandwich
description: An open-faced sandwich of a half section of Italian or French bread, spread with garlic butter and topped with ham and either Provel or Provolone cheese, seasoned with a sprinkling of paprika, and then toasted.

name: Horseshoe sandwich
description: An open-faced sandwich of thick-sliced toasted bread, a hamburger patty or other meat, French fries, and a cheese sauce that is somewhat similar to Welsh rarebit.

name: Hot brown
description: An open-faced sandwich of turkey with sliced tomatoes on thick-cut toast, covered with Mornay sauce and topped with bacon, and baked or broiled until the bread is crisp and the sauce begins to brown.

name: Italian beef
description: A sandwich of thin slices of seasoned roast beef, dripping with meat juices, on a dense, long Italian-style roll.

name: Jibarito
description: A jibarito (/ˌhiːbəˈriːtoʊ/ HEE-bə-REE-toh) is a sandwich, inspired by the cuisine of Puerto Rico, made with flattened, fried green plantains instead of bread.  Generally with a thin steak filling, or sometimes chicken or pork.  Usually topped with garlic-flavored mayonnaise, lettuce, and tomato.

name: Jucy Lucy
description: A cheeseburger that has the cheese inside the meat patty instead of on top.

name: Mother-in-law
description: A tamale in a hot dog bun, covered with chili.

name: Muffuletta
description: A sandwich on a muffuletta bread, a large, round, and light Italian bread with sesame seeds.  It's filled with various meats and cheeses, usually including ham, salami, mortadella, Swiss cheese, and provolone, with olive salad spread on the bread.

name: Pepper and egg sandwich
description: Scrambled eggs and grilled bell peppers on French bread.

name: Pilgrim sandwich
description: Also known as a Thanksgiving sandwich.  Made with sliced turkey, stuffing, cranberry sauce, and sometimes cheese and other ingredients.

name: Pit beef sandwich
description: A sandwich of charcoal-roasted beef, sliced and served rare on a Kaiser roll.

name: Po' boy
description: A submarine sandwich on a wide piece of French bread that is crunchy on the outside and light on the inside.  Popular fillings include fried seafood such as shrimp, oysters, or catfish, and the more traditional roast beef with brown gravy.  Usually topped ("dressed") with shredded lettuce, tomatoes, pickles, and mayonnaise.

name: Reuben sandwich
description: A hot sandwich composed of corned beef, Swiss cheese, sauerkraut, and Russian or Thousand Island dressing, grilled between slices of rye bread.

name: Sailor sandwich
description: A sandwich of grilled knackwurst, hot pastrami, melted Swiss cheese, and spicy mustard on rye bread.

name: Sloppy joe
description: In most of the U.S., a sloppy joe is a sandwich of ground beef and tomato sauce, with onion and spices, served on a hamburger bun.  But in North Jersey, a sloppy joe is a double decker thin sliced rye bread sandwich made with one or more types of sliced deli meat, such as turkey, ham, pastrami, corned beef, roast beef, or sliced beef tongue, along with Swiss cheese, coleslaw, and Russian dressing.

name: Spiedie
description: A spiedie (/ˈspiːdi/ SPEE-dee) is a sandwich of marinated cubes of lamb, chicken, pork, or beef served on Italian bread or white bread.

name: St. Paul sandwich
description: An egg foo young patty on white bread, with dill pickle slices, lettuce, tomatoes, and mayonnaise.

name: Submarine sandwich
description: Also known as a sub, wedge, hoagie, hero, grinder, baguette and other names, it originated in several different Italian American communities in the Northeastern United States from the late 19th to mid-20th centuries.  A long roll of bread split widthwise into two pieces, and filled with a variety of meats, cheeses, vegetables, seasonings, and sauces.

name: Tavern sandwich
description: Also known as a loosemeat sandwich, it contains crumbled, unseasoned ground beef on a bun, mixed with sauteed onions, and sometimes topped with pickles, ketchup and mustard.

name: Brunswick stew
description: A stew based on tomatoes, local beans and vegetables, and chicken in recent times; originally, small game meat such as squirrel, rabbit or opossum was used instead.

name: Burgoo
description: A spicy stew,

name: Gumbo
description: A meat or seafood soup or stew thickened with okra or filé.

name: She-crab soup
description: A seafood soup made with blue crab meat, crab roe, and crab stock mixed with heavy cream and dry sherry.

name: Vichyssoise
description: Vichyssoise (/viːʃiːˈswɑːz/ vee-shee-SWAHZ) is a thick soup made of puréed leeks, onions, potatoes, cream, and chicken stock.  Its origins is a subject of debate among culinary historians; Julia Child calls it "an American invention",

name: Yaka mein
description: A soup that combines influences of Chinese and Creole cuisine.  Stewed beef in beef-based broth with noodles, garnished with half a hard-boiled egg and chopped green onions, with Creole or Cajun seasoning.

name: Carne asada fries
description: French fries, carne asada, guacamole, sour cream, and cheese.

name: Chicken fried steak
description: A breaded cutlet dish consisting of a piece of tenderized cube steak coated with seasoned flour and pan fried.

name: Delmonico steak
description: A method of preparation from one of several cuts of beef (typically the Rib Cut) prepared Delmonico style, made by Delmonico's Restaurant during the mid-19th century.

name: Finger steaks
description: Small strips of steak (usually sirloin), battered with a tempura-like batter and deep-fried in oil. Typically served with French fries and fry sauce, and a thick piece of buttered toast.

name: Steak de Burgo
description: Usually consists of a beef tenderloin either topped with butter, garlic, and Italian herbs, or served in a sauce consisting of those same ingredients

name: Steak Diane
description: A pan-fried beefsteak with a sauce made from the seasoned pan juices, generally prepared in restaurants tableside, and flambéed. It does not appear in the classics of French cuisine, and was probably invented in the mid-20th century as part of the fad for tableside-flambéed dishes.
